        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Google Search Console (GSC)</strong> is a free platform from Google that shows exactly how your website performs in Google Search. It reports which queries earn clicks, which pages are indexed, and what technical problems Google encounters while crawling your site — all from Google's own systems, not estimates.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Cost</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Free (no paid tier)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Analytics &amp; SEO Tools</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Data history</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Up to 16 months</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If you're doing any form of SEO and haven't set up Search Console, you're flying blind. Every other tool — Ahrefs, Semrush, Moz — gives you estimated data. GSC gives you the actual numbers straight from Google's systems, with over 10 million verified properties worldwide.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Google Search Console?</h2>
        <p>Google Search Console is Google's own interface for website owners, SEOs, and developers to understand how Googlebot interacts with their site and how their pages appear in search results. Originally launched as Google Webmaster Tools in 2006 and rebranded to Search Console in 2015, it has become the most widely used SEO tool globally — and it costs nothing.</p>
        <p>GSC serves as a direct communication channel between site owners and Google. It shows:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Which queries your pages appear for</strong> — and how many clicks and impressions each earns</li>
          <li><strong>Which pages Google has indexed</strong> — and why others were excluded</li>
          <li><strong>Technical issues Google finds</strong> — Core Web Vitals failures, mobile usability problems, crawl errors</li>
          <li><strong>Manual actions and security alerts</strong> — if Google penalises or flags your site</li>
          <li><strong>Structured data status</strong> — whether your schema markup is valid and generating rich results</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why GSC data is different</div>
          <p>Third-party tools like Ahrefs and Semrush estimate rankings by crawling search results or buying clickstream data samples. GSC reports <strong>actual clicks and impressions from Google's systems</strong>. A page might show "position 4" in both tools, but only GSC knows if that generated 40 clicks or 400.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Google Search Console matters for SEO</h2>
        <p>GSC provides the verified, first-party data on which all other SEO decisions should be grounded. Five concrete reasons it belongs in every SEO workflow:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Real click and impression data.</strong> GSC shows actual clicks, impressions, CTR, and average position for every query your site appears for. No sampling, no estimation. This is the only way to know whether your ranking improvements are generating actual traffic.</li>
          <li><strong>Indexing visibility.</strong> Shows exactly which pages Google has indexed, which are excluded, and why — duplicate content, noindex tags, canonical conflicts, crawl budget overruns. You cannot fix what you cannot see.</li>
          <li><strong>Technical issue alerts.</strong> GSC proactively notifies you about Core Web Vitals failures, mobile usability problems, and manual actions — often before you notice a traffic drop.</li>
          <li><strong>Direct communication with Google.</strong> Submit URLs for indexing, request a site recrawl, and submit sitemaps directly. No third-party intermediary.</li>
          <li><strong>Link intelligence.</strong> See your top linked pages, which external domains link to you most, and how internal links are distributed — all from Google's crawl data.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google Search Console works</h2>
        <p>GSC collects data from Google's search infrastructure and presents it through a dashboard at <code>search.google.com/search-console</code>. Before accessing data, you verify site ownership.</p>

        <h3>Verification methods</h3>
        <p>Google offers five verification methods: DNS record, HTML file upload, HTML meta tag, Google Analytics connection, or Google Tag Manager. DNS verification is most reliable — it doesn't depend on a file remaining accessible or a tag staying on every page. Data typically appears within 48-72 hours after verification, with full historical data populating over several days.</p>

        <h3>Core reports</h3>
        <p>The Performance report is the most-used feature. It displays clicks, impressions, average CTR, and average position for every query and page. Filter by date range, country, device, search appearance, or query type. This is where you find high-impression, low-click pages — the fastest wins in SEO.</p>
        <p>The Pages report (formerly Coverage report) shows indexing status for every URL Google knows about. Pages fall into: indexed, excluded, errors, and valid with warnings. Sudden spikes in excluded pages usually signal technical problems requiring immediate attention.</p>
        <p>The URL Inspection tool lets you enter any URL and receive Google's assessment: indexing status, last crawl date, rendered HTML, and mobile usability issues. You can also request indexing directly from this tool, cutting time to first-crawl from weeks to days for important new pages.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Google Search Console report types explained</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Report section</th><th>What it shows</th><th>When to use it</th></tr>
            </thead>
