        <h2 id="examples">Real Google Search Console examples</h2>
        <p>These are the three scenarios where GSC produces the most direct, measurable impact.</p>

        <h3>1. Discovering hidden keyword opportunities</h3>
        <p>A local dentist checks the Performance report and finds 2,400 monthly impressions for "emergency dentist near me" — but only 12 clicks at average position 14.2. That's a 0.5% CTR on a high-intent query. After optimising the emergency services page with targeted on-page SEO, the page climbs to position 6 with 180 monthly clicks within 6 weeks. The keyword existed. GSC made it visible.</p>

        <h3>2. Finding and fixing indexing problems</h3>
        <p>A small ecommerce store notices organic traffic dropping 30% over six weeks. The Pages report reveals 340 product pages showing "Discovered — currently not indexed." A faulty <code>robots.txt</code> rule blocking the <code>/products/</code> directory is the culprit. Fixing one line restores indexing for all 340 pages within two weeks. Without GSC, this would take months to diagnose.</p>

        <h3>3. Monitoring content performance over time</h3>
        <p>A pest control company publishes 30 SEO articles monthly. After three months, GSC's Performance report shows which articles gain impressions and clicks over time. Articles ranking 11-20 become optimisation targets — they have traction but need better internal linking or content depth to break onto page one.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Google Search Console vs. Google Analytics — which to use</h2>
        <p>Both tools are free and both are essential. They answer different questions.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use Google Search Console when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You want to know which queries bring visitors</li>
              <li>You need to check indexing status of pages</li>
              <li>You're diagnosing a traffic drop</li>
              <li>You want to verify structured data is valid</li>
              <li>You're monitoring Core Web Vitals across the site</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use Google Analytics when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You want to know what visitors do after arriving</li>
              <li>You're tracking conversions and goal completions</li>
              <li>You need session, bounce rate, or engagement data</li>
              <li>You're measuring content against revenue</li>
              <li>You want cross-channel attribution</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 Google Search Console best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Check the Performance report weekly.</strong> Look for queries with high impressions but low CTR — these are the fastest wins. A page averaging position 8 with 3,000 impressions and 1% CTR can double clicks with a title tag improvement alone.</li>
          <li><strong>Submit your sitemap immediately after verification.</strong> In the Sitemaps section, submit your XML sitemap. Update it whenever you add significant new content. GSC uses it to discover new pages faster than crawl-discovery alone.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor the Pages report monthly.</strong> Watch for pages shifting from indexed to excluded. Sudden spikes in excluded pages signal technical problems — faulty canonicals, accidental noindex tags, or robots.txt changes.</li>
          <li><strong>Use URL Inspection for new important pages.</strong> After publishing any page you care about ranking, paste its URL into the Inspection tool and click "Request Indexing." This cuts indexing time from weeks to days.</li>
          <li><strong>Set up email alerts.</strong> Configure GSC email notifications for critical issues — manual actions, security problems, and indexing spikes. Route them to an inbox someone checks at least weekly.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — ignoring the impressions data</div>
          <p>Most GSC users focus on clicks and miss the impressions column. A page with 5,000 impressions and 50 clicks (1% CTR) is ranking but failing to convert searchers. Fixing the title and meta description can triple clicks without any content changes. The data is right there — most SEOs ignore it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Google Search Console mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Not verifying all URL variants.</strong> Add both www and non-www versions, and both http and https. GSC treats them as separate properties — you need data from all of them.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring excluded pages.</strong> "Discovered — currently not indexed" is not a benign status. Pages stuck in this state are invisible to Google and earning zero traffic.</li>
          <li><strong>Requesting indexing for every page.</strong> The indexing request tool has a rate limit. Use it for important new pages, not every post or product.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating position as an absolute rank.</strong> Average position in GSC is the mean across all searches — desktop, mobile, different locations. A page at "position 5" may rank 2nd in one country and 12th in another.</li>
          <li><strong>Checking GSC daily.</strong> Most metrics update with a 2-3 day lag. Daily checking creates noise. Weekly review cadence is optimal for most sites.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
